text:
Congress Street, north from King to West Houston Streets.
About 1921.

11-1 King Street, north side, and 8-2, east side, east from Congress Street (which will become the west side of the future Sixth Avenue Extension at this point). NOS. 13-7, at the left, and 8 and 6, the three-story houses on the right, will be demolished when the new subway and Sixth Avenue Extension (q.v.) are put through, beginning the year after. No. 9-5, adjoining the N.E. corner of Congress Street, is the abandoned building of the Alexander Presbyterian Church. 1926.

original_title: Manhattan: 6th Avenue - King Street to Charlton Street.
text:
(1)
Sixth Avenue Extension, east side, from King to Charlton Streets, showing 2 and 4 King Street, at and adjoining the south corner of Macdougal, and the rear of 35 and 33 Macdougal Street, frame houses with brick fronts. These two houses will later be demolished, but Nos. 37 and 39, which are hidden by 4-2 King Street, will remain.
September 1, 1928.

P. L. Sperr.

(2)
The same, showing an extended view. Shown through clearance are Nos. 34 to 20 MacDougal Street, at, adjoining and south of the S.E. corner of Prince Street.
September 1, 1928.

P. L. Sperr.

15-25 King Street, at and adjoining the N.W. corner of Congress Street (Sixth Avenue Extension). Between No. 21, the second three-story house, and No. 21½, the first five-story tenement, passes the old property line dividing the West Bayard Farm, on the east, from the Trinity Church Farm, on the west. The three tenement houses stand on the site of what was the "True Dutch Reformed Church" in the 1850's, but was later abandoned and used as a stable for some years. October 19, 1928.

P. L. Sperr.

Sixth Avenue, west side, from King (left) to West Houston Streets. This building line was originally the westerly side of the former Congress Street. It lost its identity in 1928 on the extension of the Avenue southward. For photos of same see files under the Congress Street heading.

April 30, 1940

P. L. Sperr
